"Franchito S.H., Brahmananda Rao V., Moraes E.C.","Impact of global warming on the geobotanic zones: An experiment with a statistical-dynamical climate model",2011,"Climate Dynamics","37","9-10",,"2021","2034",,,10.1007/s00382-010-0952-6,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-80355147448&partnerID=40&md5=cc6779766013b57f978f31e78d86c6e5","Centro de Ciência do Sistema Terrestre, CCST, Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, São Jose dos Campos, CP 515, Sãu Paulo, SP 12245-970, Brazil; Divisão de Sensoriamento Remoto, DSR, Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, São Jose dos Campos, CP 515, Sãu Paulo, SP 12245-970, Brazil","Franchito, S.H., Centro de Ciência do Sistema Terrestre, CCST, Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, São Jose dos Campos, CP 515, Sãu Paulo, SP 12245-970, Brazil; Brahmananda Rao, V., Centro de Ciência do Sistema Terrestre, CCST, Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, São Jose dos Campos, CP 515, Sãu Paulo, SP 12245-970, Brazil; Moraes, E.C., Divisão de Sensoriamento Remoto, DSR, Instituto Nacional de Pesquisas Espaciais, São Jose dos Campos, CP 515, Sãu Paulo, SP 12245-970, Brazil","In this study, a zonally-averaged statistical climate model (SDM) is used to investigate the impact of global warming on the distribution of the geobotanic zones over the globe. The model includes a parameterization of the biogeophysical feedback mechanism that links the state of surface to the atmosphere (a bidirectional interaction between vegetation and climate). In the control experiment (simulation of the present-day climate) the geobotanic state is well simulated by the model, so that the distribution of the geobotanic zones over the globe shows a very good agreement with the observed ones. The impact of global warming on the distribution of the geobotanic zones is investigated considering the increase of CO2 concentration for the B1, A2 and A1FI scenarios. The results showed that the geobotanic zones over the entire earth can be modified in future due to global warming. Expansion of subtropical desert and semi-desert zones in the Northern and Southern Hemispheres, retreat of glaciers and sea-ice, with the Arctic region being particularly affected and a reduction of the tropical rainforest and boreal forest can occur due to the increase of the greenhouse gases concentration. The effects were more pronounced in the A1FI and A2 scenarios compared with the B1 scenario. The SDM results confirm IPCC AR4 projections of future climate and are consistent with simulations of more complex GCMs, reinforcing the necessity of the mitigation of climate change associated to global warming. © 2010 Springer-Verlag.","Geobotanic zones distribution; Global warming; Interaction between the atmosphere and vegetation; Statistical-dynamical model","atmosphere-biosphere interaction; botany; climate effect; climate modeling; feedback mechanism; global warming; greenhouse gas; Northern Hemisphere; parameterization; Southern Hemisphere; statistical analysis",,,,,,"Adem, J., On the theory of the general circulation of the atmosphere (1962) Tellus, 14, pp. 102-115; Adler, R.F., Huffman, G.J., Chang, A., Ferraro, R., Xie, P., Janowiak, J., Rudolf, B., Arkin, P., The version 2 global precipitation climatology project (GPCP) monthly precipitation analysis (1979-Present) (2003) J Hydrometeor, 4, pp. 1147-1167; Betts, R.A., Cox, P.M., Collins, M., Harris, P.P., Huntingford, C., Jones, C.D., The role of ecosystem-atmosphere interactions in simulated Amazonian precipitation decrease and forest dieback under global climate warming (2004) Theor Appl Climatol, 78, pp. 157-175; Budyko, M.I., (1974) Climate and Life, p. 508. , London: Academic Press; Budyko, M.I., Balancing the global heat budget (1978) Climate Change, pp. 85-113. , In: Gribbin J, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Campbell, G.C., Vonder Haar, T.H., (1980) Climatology of Radiation Budget Measurements From Satellite, Atmos Sci Pap 323, p. 74. , Department of Atmosphe